1. Namespaces (environment separation)


What is a Namespace?

A Namespace is:

A logical boundary inside Kubernetes

Think:

One cluster → multiple environments

Example:

dev
qa
staging
prod
🧠 Why we need it

Without namespace:

All apps mixed together ❌
Name conflicts ❌
Hard to manage ❌

With namespace:

Isolation ✅
Organization ✅
Access control ✅

🔧 Create namespace
kubectl create namespace dev

What this does
creates a logical container called dev
all resources inside it are isolated

Use namespace
kubectl get pods -n dev
Meaning
-n dev → operate inside dev namespace
🧠 Important concept

Same app name can exist in different namespaces:

dev/my-app
prod/my-app

They don’t conflict.



2. Readiness Probe (VERY IMPORTANT)
🧠 Problem it solves

Without readiness:

Pod starts → Kubernetes sends traffic immediately ❌

But your app might still be:

loading
connecting to DB
not ready
🧠 What readinessProbe does
"Is this app ready to serve traffic?"

If NOT ready:

Kubernetes will NOT send traffic
🔧 Example

```
readinessProbe:
  httpGet:
    path: /health
    port: 5000
  initialDelaySeconds: 5
  periodSeconds: 5
```

🧠 Deep explanation
httpGet

Kubernetes sends:

GET /health

to your app.

initialDelaySeconds: 5
Wait 5 seconds before first check

Why?

App needs time to start.

periodSeconds: 5
Check every 5 seconds
🧠 Result

If /health returns success:

Pod becomes READY

If not:

Pod = NOT READY → no traffic





3. Liveness Probe
🧠 Problem it solves

What if app:

starts fine
but later hangs or crashes silently?

Without liveness:

Kubernetes does nothing ❌
🧠 What livenessProbe does
"Is this app still alive?"

If NOT:

Kubernetes restarts the container
🔧 Example


```
livenessProbe:
  httpGet:
    path: /health
    port: 5000
  initialDelaySeconds: 10
  periodSeconds: 10
```


🧠 Difference from readiness
Probe	Purpose
readiness	should receive traffic?
liveness	should restart container?
🧠 Important insight
readiness = traffic control
liveness = self-healing




4. Resource Requests & Limits
🧠 Problem

Without limits:

One container can use all CPU/memory ❌
Other apps crash ❌
Node becomes unstable ❌
🧠 Solution

Kubernetes lets you define:

requests → minimum needed
limits → maximum allowed
🔧 Example

``` 
resources:
  requests:
    memory: "128Mi"
    cpu: "100m"
  limits:
    memory: "256Mi"
    cpu: "200m"
🧠 Explanation
requests
Scheduler guarantees this much

Example:

Need at least 128MB RAM
limits
Cannot exceed this

If exceeded:

Container may be killed (OOMKilled)
🧠 CPU unit
100m = 0.1 CPU
1000m = 1 CPU





5. Rolling Update Strategy
🧠 What you used so far

Default rolling update.

But let’s understand control.

🔧 Example
strategy:
  type: RollingUpdate
  rollingUpdate:
    maxUnavailable: 0
    maxSurge: 1
🧠 Meaning
maxUnavailable: 0
Never reduce running pods below desired

→ ensures zero downtime

maxSurge: 1
Allow 1 extra pod during update
🧠 Example flow (replicas=1)
Old pod running
↓
Create 1 new pod
↓
Wait until ready
↓
Delete old pod




